{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622141"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:00:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:00:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16787"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16787"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9478"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77295"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9478"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16787"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62802"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5236"},{"type":"tags","id":"5244"},{"type":"tags","id":"7614"},{"type":"tags","id":"7669"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22408"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22895"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77295"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETopoisomerase I is an enzyme that relieves torsional strain in DNA during replication by creating temporary single-strand breaks that allows the DNA strand to loosen and unwind. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of topoisomerase I inhibitors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks enzyme attachment to DNA strands","Causes direct DNA strand breakage","Prevents DNA synthesis","Stabilising the DNA-topoisomerase I complex","Creates two-strand breaks in DNA"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETopoisomerase I inhibitors work by \u003Cstrong\u003Estabilising the DNA-topoisomerase I complex\u003C/strong\u003E. When the replication fork meets these stabilised complexes, the unmitigated torsional stress of the tightly coiled DNA strands causes double-strand DNA breaks that trigger apoptosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks enzyme attachment to DNA strands\u003C/strong\u003E: these drugs require the enzyme to bind to DNA first before they can exert their effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECauses direct DNA strand breakage\u003C/strong\u003E: these drugs do not directly damage DNA strands, but rather prevent topoisomerase I from mending the single-strand breaks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents DNA synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E: not the mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreates two-strand breaks in DNA\u003C/strong\u003E: this is the normal mechanism of action of topoisomerase II. Just as topoisomerase I works to cause single-strand breaks in double stranded DNA, topoisomerase II works to cause double-strand breaks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamples of topoisomerase I inhibitors include irinotecan and topotecan. These drugs are effective against  cancer cells where DNA replication rapidly occurs. Topoisomerase II inhibitors also have therapeutic purposes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClinical applications include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIrinotecan: metastatic colorectal cancer\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETopotecan: ovarian cancer, small cell lung cancer, cervical cancer\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon adverse effects include bone marrow suppression, diarrhoea, and nausea due to their effects on rapidly dividing normal cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Topoisomerase I inhibitors prevent DNA unwinding by stabilising the DNA-topoisomerase I complex, which leads to double stranded DNA breaks and apoptosis.","Topoisomerase I inhibitors are derived from camptothecin and include irinotecan and topotecan.","Topoisomerase I inhibitors are particularly effective against rapidly dividing cells and are used to treat various cancers including colorectal, ovarian, and small cell lung cancer."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62802"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16787"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62802"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T15:35:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T15:36:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9478"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77295"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}}